1
00:00:00,470 --> 00:00:27,692
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha

2
00:00:27,975 --> 00:00:34,122
the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:34,143 --> 00:00:42,792
So, we're looking this evening at the business of family.

4
00:00:43,694 --> 00:00:47,137
And we'll start with parents.

5
00:00:48,139 --> 00:00:55,627
So whenever you offer loving kindness in the practice, you always start with your parents.

6
00:00:56,607 --> 00:00:57,408
And

7
00:00:59,600 --> 00:01:13,215
This is what he says about them.

8
00:01:14,177 --> 00:01:21,025
There are five ways in which a son should minister to his mother and father as the eastern direction.

9
00:01:21,486 --> 00:01:27,733
Now, we have to take for granted that this is a patriarchal society and sons are the only ones that matter.

10
00:01:29,349 --> 00:01:31,332
That's a bit cheeky.

11
00:01:31,352 --> 00:01:33,536
For son, read son and daughter.

12
00:01:36,179 --> 00:01:40,185
He should think, having been supported by them, I will support them.

13
00:01:41,006 --> 00:01:42,888
I will perform their duties for them.

14
00:01:43,448 --> 00:01:45,272
I will keep up the family tradition.

15
00:01:45,933 --> 00:01:48,055
I will be worthy of my heritage.

16
00:01:48,596 --> 00:01:52,762
And after my parents' death, I will distribute gifts on their behalf.

17
00:01:54,364 --> 00:01:58,750
And there are five directions in which parents, so ministered to by their sons,

18
00:01:58,983 --> 00:02:24,282
in the eastern direction will reciprocate will reciprocate they will restrain him from evil support him in doing good teach him some skill find him a suitable wife and in due time hand over his inheritance to him and in this way the eastern direction is covered making it at peace and free from fear remember all these little things are always always ending up with

19
00:02:24,633 --> 00:02:50,133
making it at peace and free from fear so we have to accept that the Buddha lived at a particular time but most of what he says still pertains today having been supported by them I will support them these days more and more people

20
00:02:50,435 --> 00:02:56,302
They're going to have to look after their elderly parents, especially baby boomers like my generation.

21
00:02:56,984 --> 00:02:59,366
And for some, it's very little.

22
00:03:00,868 --> 00:03:03,292
But for others, it's going to be a full-time job.

23
00:03:03,913 --> 00:03:18,432
And this whole business of duty, if you feel that something is imposed upon you as a must, as an ought to, as an outside duty, then obviously it becomes a burden.

24
00:03:20,287 --> 00:03:27,854
But when you take it on as your personal responsibility, then it becomes something that you are very happy to take on.

25
00:03:29,115 --> 00:03:29,936
That's the distinction.

26
00:03:30,675 --> 00:03:39,704
So often when you get in popular psychology, this business of must and ought to are terrible things, it's good to make that distinction.

27
00:03:41,566 --> 00:03:49,212
And of course, just by contemplating what our parents did for us, that one raises a certain sense of gratitude.

28
00:03:49,682 --> 00:03:55,769
And with that gratitude, there comes a desire to fulfill our commitments, our duties.

29
00:03:57,330 --> 00:04:01,914
I suppose the other thing is, ever since Freud, we've blamed our parents for everything that's wrong with us.

30
00:04:02,735 --> 00:04:05,778
So it became fashionable to hate your mother especially.

31
00:04:06,258 --> 00:04:16,990
So there's a case of also recognizing that our parents were probably more enlightened than we are, but definitely unenlightened.

32
00:04:17,358 --> 00:04:19,240
And therefore, just did their best.

33
00:04:19,540 --> 00:04:20,903
Most of them did their best, you know.

34
00:04:22,245 --> 00:04:25,290
And some of them would have been through rough times for various reasons.

35
00:04:25,971 --> 00:04:27,533
And that's the way it is.

36
00:04:27,894 --> 00:04:30,257
That's the way it probably was in the Buddha's time.

37
00:04:31,098 --> 00:04:33,661
These days, of course, society is a bit more fraught.

38
00:04:34,543 --> 00:04:42,235
In his day, it was a much more agrarian society, much more gentle, easy-moving.

39
00:04:43,235 --> 00:04:44,158
There were hard times.

40
00:04:44,197 --> 00:04:45,019
There were famines.

41
00:04:45,538 --> 00:04:48,723
There was one definitely during the Buddha's time.

42
00:04:48,744 --> 00:04:49,625
It wasn't all easy.

43
00:04:51,348 --> 00:04:53,692
And there were local skirmishes, local wars.

44
00:04:54,894 --> 00:05:04,511
So it wasn't... Well, we know that his family was, or his people, the Sakyas, were attacked by the local king, the Dudduba.

45
00:05:04,531 --> 00:05:06,533
And they had to shift capital.

46
00:05:06,574 --> 00:05:09,319
So there would have been lots of suffering there.

47
00:05:10,918 --> 00:05:19,593
But it is this business of just looking at what we mean when we say must and ought to, our duty, duty and responsibility.

48
00:05:20,254 --> 00:05:25,524
It tends to be against the modern grain because we tend to prefer to talk about rights.

49
00:05:28,447 --> 00:05:29,048
My right.

50
00:05:29,689 --> 00:05:34,939
So if we say it's my right to look after my parents, then it's all right.

51
00:05:34,959 --> 00:05:37,163
I have a right to look after my parents.

52
00:05:38,358 --> 00:05:41,000
And I'll perform their duties for them.

53
00:05:41,221 --> 00:05:42,744
I keep up the family tradition.

54
00:05:45,526 --> 00:05:51,574
That's an interesting one, which might not pertain very much these days.

55
00:05:52,096 --> 00:05:59,365
But you know, when I began to practice Buddhism, this was against the tradition of the family.

56
00:05:59,386 --> 00:06:04,331
The family were, by generations upon generations, Catholics on both sides.

57
00:06:06,016 --> 00:06:15,024
And I remember when I ordained as a monk, my parents, my brothers and sisters came.

58
00:06:16,646 --> 00:06:19,408
I wrote to my uncle, my one and only uncle.

59
00:06:20,509 --> 00:06:21,430
That's my English uncle.

60
00:06:21,471 --> 00:06:23,874
My mother's Italian, so I had uncles over there.

61
00:06:24,494 --> 00:06:27,877
But my only English uncle, I said, you know, I invited him to come.

62
00:06:27,978 --> 00:06:33,343
And he said he couldn't, he said, because I'd abandoned the faith of my father.

63
00:06:34,423 --> 00:06:34,504
See?

64
00:06:35,192 --> 00:06:42,202
So there are certain unspoken traditions in the family.

65
00:06:42,483 --> 00:06:50,173
One of them might be that nobody's ever been to prison and you've ended up in prison.

66
00:06:51,836 --> 00:06:59,747
Or in the older days, again, a lot of these things are much looser now, but divorce, you know, like, I just can't remember.

67
00:06:59,766 --> 00:07:01,369
Oh, yes, that's right.

68
00:07:01,906 --> 00:07:06,492
In Sri Lanka, you see, the man who looked after our monastery is an elderly fellow.

69
00:07:07,394 --> 00:07:14,966
He was talking to me about his personal life one day and he was saying to me, you know, it was a terrible marriage and I wanted to divorce.

70
00:07:15,326 --> 00:07:18,252
So I went to my parents and said, you know, I want a divorce.

71
00:07:18,271 --> 00:07:21,257
And they said, well, we don't do that, so I never divorced.

72
00:07:24,422 --> 00:07:28,267
So in certain families you do get this very strong tradition, you know.

73
00:07:29,935 --> 00:07:55,233
I'll be worthy of their heritage well you know and then after my parents death I'll distribute gifts on their behalf so this is to do with you know helping people through good works passing on your merit to other people and also in most religions you

74
00:07:55,416 --> 00:08:00,663
You do things, don't you, for your parents in Buddhism.

75
00:08:00,684 --> 00:08:12,019
Whenever you offer something to the monastery, whenever you give something to the monastery, you always do a pirit, and it's always for your relatives who've died.

76
00:08:13,060 --> 00:08:14,180
It's always for their benefit.

77
00:08:14,961 --> 00:08:15,923
Always bring that to mind.

78
00:08:19,187 --> 00:08:24,714
On the other hand, of course, parents have a duty to their children, and they reciprocate it, you see.

79
00:08:25,166 --> 00:08:28,411
And they restrain them from evil.

80
00:08:30,452 --> 00:08:36,479
So we hear a lot of these days of blaming parents for the way some of the children behave.

81
00:08:45,408 --> 00:08:46,730
It's very difficult, isn't it?

82
00:08:46,750 --> 00:08:53,638
Because these days a lot of teenagers have their own minds and some of these families are under a lot of social strain.

83
00:08:54,427 --> 00:09:22,511
but you know they try and do their best but they blame parents the newspapers blame parents for all these kids that were out rioting and what not but some of them are untrainable aren't they you might be interested to know that there was a book published just after those riots in London called the Gangs of Manchester believe it or not

84
00:09:23,722 --> 00:09:49,360
which went back to the late 1900s exactly the same problem with riots by the youth and all that and the same thing papers going on about parents duties and all that and what they did was set up working men's clubs which taught them which educated the poor people and gave them skills

85
00:09:49,913 --> 00:10:19,110
and eventually found them work and it took a generation so that's what we're in for now all those working men's clubs have disappeared haven't they it's been years since I've seen those and to find him to teach him a skill you see educational to find him a suitable wife so that's gone out of fashion hasn't it and in due time to hand over their inheritance so that's the

86
00:10:19,342 --> 00:10:49,332
these are to be taken as things just to contemplate about our own relationship to our parents and our children but here he talks about how much we owe them so this is how important he understood parents to be he said monks I declare that there are two people one can never repay what two

87
00:10:49,549 --> 00:10:50,971
one's mother and father.

88
00:10:51,972 --> 00:11:19,471
Even if one should carry about one's mother on one shoulder and one's father on the other, and while doing so should live a hundred years, reach the age of a hundred years, and if one should attend to them by anointing them with balms, by massaging, bathing, and rubbing their limbs, and they should even void their excrements there, even by that would one not do enough for one's parents, nor would one repay them.

89
00:11:19,874 --> 00:11:20,495
That's good, isn't it?

90
00:11:22,697 --> 00:11:34,668
Even if one were to establish one's parents as the supreme lords and rulers over the earth, so rich in the seven treasures, one would not do enough for them, nor would one repay them.

91
00:11:34,687 --> 00:11:35,607
For what reasons?

92
00:11:36,048 --> 00:11:38,150
Parents are of great help to their children.

93
00:11:38,530 --> 00:11:41,533
They bring them up, feed them, and show them the world.

94
00:11:42,615 --> 00:11:47,078
So that's his way of expressing our gratitude to our parents.

95
00:11:47,479 --> 00:11:48,159
However,

96
00:11:49,269 --> 00:12:19,226
But monks, one who encourages his unbelieving parents, settles them and establishes them in the faith, who encourages his immoral parents, settles and establishes them in moral discipline, who encourages his stingy parents, settles and establishes them in generosity, who encourages his ignorant parents, settles and establishes them in wisdom,

97
00:12:19,595 --> 00:12:49,163
such a one does enough for his parents he repays them and more than repays them for what they have done so there is a way of repaying your parents and that is basically to establish them in the Buddha's dispensation which is a bit much these days isn't it but that gives you an idea of his of the way that parents were treated in his day

98
00:12:49,767 --> 00:12:53,291
And you still get that in the East.

99
00:12:53,311 --> 00:12:56,134
You still get a special honouring of parents.

100
00:12:57,134 --> 00:13:00,038
I'm not so sure we do that these days so much.

101
00:13:01,620 --> 00:13:16,517
So that gives you an idea of his advice or his guidance when it comes to dealing with our parents and how parents should deal with their children.

102
00:13:20,767 --> 00:13:24,355
So I think that brings us to the end of this evening's little homily.

103
00:13:26,359 --> 00:13:32,633
It'll take me a while to get through his whole thing, but this time next year I should have just about made it.

104
00:13:32,653 --> 00:13:35,057
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

105
00:13:35,619 --> 00:13:47,365
May you be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

